---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import SectionHeader from '../../components/SectionHeader.astro';
import PullQuote from '../../components/PullQuote.astro';
import Annotation from '../../components/Annotation.astro';
---
<Base title="The Problem With Most AI UIs" section={1}>
  <article class="prose">

    <SectionHeader
      n={1}
      title="The Problem With Most AI UIs"
      meta="~500 words"
    />

    <p>
      Open any AI interface built in the last three years and count what
      you see before you've typed a single word. Model selector. Temperature
      slider. Persona library. System prompt editor. Conversation history.
      Export button. Share button. Plugin marketplace. Each one of these
      controls represents a locally reasonable decision made by a designer
      doing their job. The aggregate is exhausting.
    </p>

    <p>
      The problem isn't that any of these features are wrong. It's that they
      all compete for the same finite resource: your attention. And attention,
      unlike compute, doesn't scale. Every visible control is a small tax
      levied against the thing you actually came to do — think.
    </p>

    <PullQuote>
      They optimized for feature visibility over cognitive flow. The interface
      confused being impressive with being useful.
    </PullQuote>

    <p>
      This is the trap of building in public during a period of rapid
      capability growth. The features are new. The users are curious.
      Showing the machinery feels like transparency, and transparency feels
      like honesty. So the temperature slider stays visible, not because users
      need it, but because hiding it feels like hiding something.
    </p>

    <p>
      But consider what a master craftsperson hides. A concert pianist
      doesn't perform with the piano lid open so the audience can watch
      the hammers. A typographer doesn't publish their kerning table alongside
      the book. The work earns its invisibility by being excellent. The same
      logic applies to software. When an interface draws attention to itself,
      it's usually because it hasn't yet solved the problem at the level of
      depth that would allow it to disappear.
    </p>

    <h2>The model selector problem</h2>

    <p>
      The model selector is the canonical example. "Which model should I
      use?" is a question that approximately zero users can answer well
      without first understanding benchmarks, pricing, context windows,
      and the specific task they're trying to accomplish. Asking users to choose is not
      empowerment — it's delegation of a decision that the interface should
      own.
    </p>

    <p>
      Compare this to how we use email. Nobody picks their SMTP server.
      Nobody chooses their mail routing path. The infrastructure is opaque
      precisely because its opacity is a feature. You get to think about
      what to write, not how to send.
    </p>

    <Annotation label="The counter-argument">
      Power users exist. They want control. This is real, and ignoring it
      produces products that experts abandon. The design challenge isn't to
      remove controls — it's to make them earn their appearance. Controls
      that are always visible are a design failure. Controls that appear
      when they're genuinely needed are a design success.
    </Annotation>

    <p>
      The sections that follow aren't a manifesto for minimalism as
      aesthetic. They're an argument for a specific kind of restraint —
      one that is hard to achieve, requires active effort to maintain, and
      produces interfaces that feel effortless precisely because they are not.
    </p>

  </article>
</Base>
